We define cofibrations and fibrations in the category of simplicial sets. Kan complexes are redefined (through an abbreviation) as fibrant objects in this category.

All the definitions look correct and reasonable but I'm wondering about the advisability about having  `CategoryWithCofibrations` and `CategoryWithFibrations` be instances and not structures.

In the future, it would be great if we could construct both the Quillen and Joyal model structures on simplicial sets, with differing notions of fibration. How do you envision this will go? 

This is not exactly relevant but in the Infinity-Cosmos project we defined equivalences in the following way
```

/-- An interval is a simplicial set equipped with two endpoints.-/
class Interval (I : SSet.{u}) : Type u where
  src : Δ[0] ⟶ I
  tgt : Δ[0] ⟶ I

/-- The interval relevant to the theory of Kan complexes.-/
instance arrowInterval : Interval Δ[1] where
  src := stdSimplex.δ (n := 0) (1)
  tgt := stdSimplex.δ (n := 0) (0)

/-- The interval relevant to the theory of quasi-categories. -/
instance isoInterval : Interval coherentIso where
  src := yonedaEquiv.symm (WalkingIso.coev WalkingIso.zero)
  tgt := yonedaEquiv.symm (WalkingIso.coev WalkingIso.one)

noncomputable def expPointIsoSelf (X : SSet) : sHom Δ[0] X ≅ X := ...

variable {I : SSet.{u}} [Interval I]

noncomputable def pathSpace {I : SSet.{u}} [Interval I] (X : SSet.{u}) : SSet.{u} := sHom I X

open MonoidalClosed

noncomputable def pathSpace.src (X : SSet.{u}) : pathSpace (I := I) X ⟶ X :=
  ((MonoidalClosed.pre Interval.src).app X ≫ X.expPointIsoSelf.hom)

noncomputable def pathSpace.tgt (X : SSet.{u}) : pathSpace (I := I) X ⟶ X :=
  ((MonoidalClosed.pre Interval.tgt).app X ≫ X.expPointIsoSelf.hom)


/-- TODO: Figure out how to allow `I` to be an a different universe from `A` and `B`?-/
structure Homotopy {A B : SSet.{u}} (f g : A ⟶ B) : Type u
    where
  homotopy : A ⟶ sHom I B
  source_eq : homotopy ≫ pathSpace.src B = f
  target_eq : homotopy ≫ pathSpace.tgt B = g

/-- For the correct interval, this defines a good notion of equivalences for both Kan complexes
and quasi-categories.-/
structure Equiv (A B : SSet.{u}) : Type u where
  toFun : A ⟶ B
  invFun : B ⟶ A
  left_inv : Homotopy (I := I) (toFun ≫ invFun) (𝟙 A)
  right_inv : Homotopy (I := I) (invFun ≫ toFun) (𝟙 B)
```

> All the definitions look correct and reasonable but I'm wondering about the advisability about having `CategoryWithCofibrations` and `CategoryWithFibrations` be instances and not structures.
> In the future, it would be great if we could construct both the Quillen and Joyal model structures on simplicial sets, with differing notions of fibration. How do you envision this will go?

For `SSet` (and also `TopCat`), I believe there is a more standard model category structure. For the Joyal structure, I would suggest using a type-synonym, and we could do the same when constructing new model category structures by Bousfield localizations.
Or maybe we can copy the measure-theory design? Where there is a "default measure", but there is notation to help plug in a different measure when you need to.

> Or maybe we can copy the measure-theory design? Where there is a "default measure", but there is notation to help plug in a different measure when you need to.

Yes, this is also a possibility, but I would suggest we wait until we have at least one or two model category structures before implementing this!

I'll concede that my point of view is less standard concerning the category of simplicial sets (using the Joyal model structure more than the Quillen one). But I don't love the idea that we'll perpetually be forced to choose a default model structure on each category. In particular, when it comes time to construct model structures on diagram categories do we pick the projective model structure as default (privileging homotopy colimits, in a sense) or the injective one (privileging homotopy limits)? Both are equally important. 

I think of the constructions of the projective/injective model structure as operations that take in a category with a model structure plus an indexing category and return a model structure on diagrams, when it exists. (Really I think of these as operations on the weak factorization systems, moreso than on the model structure, as Joël and I have discussed elsewhere.)

Chain complexes (over a ring where not all modules are projective, not a field) is another example where it's not clear to me there is a default model structure that's optimal for all applications (connecting homotopical to homological algebra).

I have made the instances "scoped". We may "load" them with `open SSet.quillenModelCategory`. When we have the luxury of choosing between two alternate model categories, we may implement either of the technical solutions to handle the situation.

:v: emilyriehl can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).

> I have made the instances "scoped". We may "load" them with `open SSet.quillenModelCategory`. When we have the luxury of choosing between two alternate model categories, we may implement either of the technical solutions to handle the situation.

Can I suggest one minor terminological change? "quillenModelCategory" -> "quillenModelStructure".

This is the language I hear folks use in talks, e.g., "equip simplicial sets with the Quillen model structure and then equip simplicial spaces with the injective model structure." Also sometimes I've heard people use the specific phrase "quillen model category" to refer to Quillen's model category axioms (to help disambiguate it from categorical logic notions, like a category of models). When I read your code I was momentarily confused by this and thought the scope was a general "quillen model category" namespace rather than a specific "Quillen model structure" namespace.

Finally, should "Quillen" be capitalized (as a proper name)? No strong feelings here but again this is what I'd do on paper.
I have changed the name as `modelCategoryQuillen`, because eventually (not very soon) this is going to be part of a definition `ModelCategory SSet`.
I like it. Thanks. If you're ready I feel like this is ready to merge?
While it's not strictly necessary I think it would be helpful to users to indicate somewhere (either in the code or the doc string that `i : Fin (n + 2)`.
Thanks for the suggestion!

pullRequest.title: feat(AlgebraicTopology): endow `SSet` with notions of cofibrations and fibrations
